    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-10-22T18:05:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-10-22T18:05:00-05:00" n="504"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d504">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">262A.84A41/10–1752: Telegram</note>
                <head>No. 504<lb/>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">Embassy in Lebanon</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d504fn1">Repeated to Amman, Cairo, Baghdad, Damascus, and
                        Bonn.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-10-22T18:05:00-05:00"
                            >October 22, 1952—6:05 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>769. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 679 Oct 3 and 798 Oct 17.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d504fn2">Neither printed.</note> Dept well aware growing Arab
                    preference interpret Bonn–Israel agreement as being imposed on Germans by US. If
                    US protests too much, Arabs feel their suspicions confirmed (Beirut 656 Sept 30)
                    but silence also can be interpreted as sign guilt.</p>
                <p>Dept suggests that on all appropriate occasions <gloss target="#t_NE1">NE</gloss>
                    Missions might try divert Arab attn by stressing (1) successful conclusion Bonn
                    agreement underscores and makes more feasible Israel’s obligation for Pal
                    refugee compensation; (2) successful efforts <gloss target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss>
                    on Israel release blocked Arab accounts; (3) <gloss target="#t_PCC1">PCC</gloss>
                    progress with Israel on determination of Arab property losses.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bruce</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
